post_text:
New this year from PSA: No need to purchase a membership to be listed in the Parent School Association Wyoming Student Directory! Find more information about the directory and membership in this message from PSA:

As many of us reviewed the PSA Wyoming Student Directory, we noted that some Wyoming families were not listed in the Directory because of the required PSA membership. We are committed to making this directory inclusive for everyone in Wyoming schools and removing barriers to participation. This year there will be no membership requirement to be included and to receive online access to the Directory. However, for privacy reasons, you will still need to "opt in" to be included. Be on the lookout for this opportunity in a follow up email. We believe this change will result in a more inclusive Wyoming Student Directory that represents our community. Families wishing to support this effort through sponsorship (donations) would be greatly appreciated. Click below for more info:
shared_text:
WYOMINGPSA.WORDPRESS.COM
Student & Family Directory

We will begin to align our In-Person Learning Level with the Ohio Public Health Advisory System starting this Monday, August 31.

During his 8/27 press conference, Governor DeWine shared that Hamilton County is currently at LEVEL 2. Based upon this, Wyoming City Schools buildings will be open to in-person learners for five days next week, starting on Monday, August 31.
text:
We will begin to align our In-Person Learning Level with the Ohio Public Health Advisory System starting this Monday, August 31.

During his 8/27 press conference, Governor DeWine shared that Hamilton County is currently at LEVEL 2. Based upon this, Wyoming City Schools buildings will be open to in-person learners for five days next week, starting on Monday, August 31.

Alumni Spotlight:
WHS Class of 2020 member Sam Bowden is participating in the Ray Bradbury Read-A-Thon of Fahrenheit 451 (along side other authors such as Neil Gaiman, Marlon James and more). Celebrating the 100th anniversary of Bradbury's birth, the read-a-thon is scheduled to premiere at raybradburyreadathon.com tomorrow and rebroadcast there through September 5. More information is available in this Rolling Stone article: https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/ray-bradbury-read-a-thon-fahrenheit-451-1044311/

post_text: How to Protect Yourself & Others: There is currently no vaccine to prevent COVID-19 and the best way to prevent illness is to avoid being exposed to this virus. Everyone should: wash hands often; avoid close contact; cover your mouth and nose with a cloth face cover when around others; cover coughs and sneezes; clean and disinfect; and monitor your health daily: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/prevention.html

post_text:
#MaskUp before going out in public. Remember, wearing a face covering protects others around you!
Your cloth face covering should:
✔️ Reach above the nose, below the chin, and completely cover the mouth and nostrils
✔️ Fit snugly against the sides of the face
✔️ Be made of multiple layers of fabric that you can still breathe through
✔️ Be able to be laundered and machine dried without damaging the material or shape
Learn more at http://ow.ly/IlU950zQylE #ResponsibleRestartOhio #OnWyoming

post_text:
Congratulations to Joshua Parker, Alex Rhodes & Elliot Wilson-Woodrow! This Wyoming High School team is one of the Top 10 finalists (out of 130 entries) in the Hamilton County Soil and Water Conservation District's Caring for our Watersheds Competition!

When asked what they could do to help their local watershed, they proposed "Going Green for Greener Lawns." The ideal lawn is thought to be green, short and free from anything besides grass, but Josh, Elliot and Alex saw how harmful this notion was to the environment. They want to collaborate with the City of Wyoming to hand out native seed packets and information on how to reduce the environmental footprint of a traditional lawn to add a little diversity, as well as more strategic uses of water and fertilizer.

#CFWOhio2020 #CaringForOurWatersheds #WhatCanYouDo #OnWyoming
shared_text:
Hamilton County Soil and Water Conservation District
June 12 at 9:34 AM ·

It's Finalist Friday! Recently, we would have hosted our final competition of the Caring for our Watersheds Ohio contest. We received over 130 entries from high school students all over the state with proposals about what they could do to help improve their local watersheds. Each Friday, we will be highlighting one of our top 10 finalists.

This week we spotlight a team from Wyoming City Schools. When asked what they could do to help their local watershed, Joshua Parker, Elliot Wilson-Woodrow and Alex Rhodes thought about all the manicured lawns in their neighborhood and realized they could help improve the environment for local insects and wildlife.

The ideal lawn is thought to be green,…

post_text:
Wyoming needs Kindness Ambassadors!
The past few weeks of isolation have been difficult for many of us. As part of the new Kindness Connection program, we are looking for volunteers to be a point of contact for your immediate neighbors. As a Kindness Ambassador, you’ll mail letters or leave notes at the door with your phone number offering to be someone who will proactively reach out and check on specific neighbors and be someone they know who cares. #WyomingStrongerTogether #KindnessConnection
For more information, visit:
https://www.wyomingrecreationfoundation.org/wkc/volunteer

post_text: The City of Wyoming has launched the Kindness Connection, a volunteer program to help us each care for one another’s mental health. There are numerous ways to help or be helped through this initiative. Learn more below:
shared_text:
Wyoming Ohio
April 24 at 4:55 PM ·

Please join our flock! Today we’re launching Kindness Connection, a volunteer program to help us each care for one another’s mental health. Some of us will lead. Others will join groups and gain the sense of togetherness we all need right now. Please follow the link below to sign up and learn more.

VOLUNTEERS NEEDED:
Kindness Ambassadors Coordinator
*Many* Kindness Ambassadors
Smile Makers Coordinator
Smile Makers
Interest Group Coordinator
Interest Group Leaders
Storyteller Group Leader
Mental Health & Wellbeing Corps Coordinator
Mental Health & Pastoral Care Volunteers
Mental Health & Wellbeing Corps Online Resource Coordinator

WANT TO JUST JOIN AND HAVE FUN?
Sign up to receive times and topics for storytelling and interest groups once we know who our leaders are. Kids who sign up to be Smile Makers can start now.

https://www.wyomingrecreationfoundation.org/wkc/information

post_text:
The funeral procession route for fallen Springdale Officer Kaia Grant has been finalized and will be held on Sunday, March 29, 2020. A wonderful way for residents to show their support to Officer Grant and her family would be to observe the procession as it travels through Wyoming. We would ask that everyone observe in a responsible manner by practicing good social distancing along the route.
The procession will leave Spring Grove Cemetery at 9 am. The route of the funeral procession through Wyoming will be:
• The procession will enter Wyoming on Route 4 from Cincinnati and proceed north
• Turn right onto Pendery Ave. (pass in front of the Wyoming High School)
• Turn left onto Burns Ave
• Turn left onto Chestnut Ave
• Turn right onto Route 4
• Continue north out of Wyoming up to Springdale
The roads will be closed to traffic during the procession so please use both sides of the road to practice responsible social distancing along the route.
-From the Wyoming Police Department

post_text: The funeral for fallen Springdale Officer and Wyoming High School Graduate Kaia Grant will be held on Sunday, March 29, 2020. Information about the processional can be found below:
shared_text:
Wyoming Police, Ohio
March 25 at 11:15 AM ·

The funeral for fallen Springdale Officer Kaia Grant will be held on Sunday, March 29, 2020. Although funerals are considered exempt from Governor DeWine’s “Shelter in Place” order, concessions will be made and we ask that all members of the community practice social distancing.

Beginning at 9am, the police procession will leave Spring Grove Cemetery. The procession will travel up State Route 4 and will pass through Wyoming on the way to its final destination of Vineyard Church in Springdale. The exact route and more specific times will be released later this week.

A wonderful way for residents to show their support to Officer Grant and her family would be to observe the procession as it travels through Wyoming. We would ask that everyone observe in a responsible manner by practicing good social distancing along the route.

In anticipation of the Governor’s executive order addressing mass gatherings, Wyoming City Schools is cancelling all gatherings of more than 150 non-students in school buildings from now until Spring Break, including tonight’s 5th-12th Grade Choir Concert and next week’s Wyoming High School National Honor Society Induction Ceremony and the Wyoming High School Winter Sports Awards. We hope to reschedule all events later in the school year.

We anticipate communicating additional information to all families later today.

Wyoming Middle School's MathCOUNTS team finished third at this weekend's competition at St. Margaret of York. Damon Cavitt led the team in points, earning one of the highest point totals of all competitors. They move on to the city-wide competition this Saturday.

“I’m so proud of the work that all of our team members do and we’re looking forward to the competition this weekend," said Team Adviser Stephanie O'Hara.

For more MathCOUNTS info, visit https://www.mathcounts.org/

Wyoming Theatre Arts presents The Addams Family this weekend at Wyoming High School!

Shows for this student production are 7:30 p.m. Friday and Saturday and at 2 p.m. on Sunday.

Tickets are $10 for adults/$7 for staff and seniors/$5 for students and are available in advance of the show at the box office at 206-7049 or online at showtix4u.com (search for The Addams Family). Tickets will also be sold at the door and at the high school during lunch on Thursday and Friday.

Once active, if you have problems accessing the site, clearing your browser cache is recommended. Questions, thoughts and suggestions can always be sent to info@wyomingcityschools.org.

post_text:
Registration is now open for Wyoming Middle School Girls Who Code Club! This club is geared to girls in grades 6-8.
Meeting times are 3:15-4:15 p.m. on Mondays January 20-May 11. Please send an email to WMS's Susan Sagan, sagans@wyomingcityschools.org to register. Include your student's name, grade, homeroom teacher, parent name and email address. Communication with the students will be via the students' school-based (Office365) email accounts.
The group welcomes women in the technology field to come and talk with the girls about their experiences. Please email Susan if you'd like to participate!

Opportunity to wish cheerleaders and football team well Saturday at 2:45 p.m. prior to state semifinal:

The Wyoming High School football team and cheerleaders will leave for the state semifinal game at 2:45 p.m. Saturday. Buses will leave the high school with a police escort, turn right on Pendery and right on Springfield Pike. Well wishers are welcome to gather along the route to celebrate the team's accomplishments.

The state semifinal game will be played at 7 p.m. Saturday vs. Clyde High School at Maryville High School (side note – their stadium is called Impact Stadium!). Address for the stadium is 800 Amrine Mill Road, Marysville, OH 43040. Gate opens at 5:30pm.

Tickets are on sale online at www.ohsaa.org/tickets right now. Tickets at the gate, if available, are $10. This is a state semifinal game so a large crowd is expected. Parking is $5 per car.

post_text:
Wyoming Youth Services Poplar Fire Benefit Fund

The Poplar house fire on Monday, Nov. 11, displaced four Wyoming families from their homes. Wyoming Youth Services, a partnership of the City of Wyoming, Wyoming City Schools and Wyoming community members, has developed a fund to be used in support of the families.

What is needed at this time?
The most immediate need is monetary assistance with food, transportation, and temporary housing.

How can I help?
Donations can be made online at GoFundMe: Poplar Benefit Fund (link below).

Donation drop boxes for cash and checks are located at the City of Wyoming Building at 800 Oak Avenue, Wyoming City Schools Central Office at 420 Springfield Pike, and at each school building. Checks can be made out to the Poplar Benefit Fund.

Questions?
Contact Wyoming Youth Services Executive Director Leslie Moorhead at 513-500-7509 or lmoorhead@wyomingyouthservices.com.

post_text:
One teaspoonful arsenic…a half teaspoon of strychnine…a pinch of cyanide…

Wyoming Theatre Arts presents the classic comedy, Arsenic and Old Lace, at the WHS Pendery Center at 7:30 p.m. Friday, Nov. 8 & 2 p.m. Sunday, Nov. 10. Tickets are $10 for Adults, $7 for Seniors and Staff, and $5 for Students. They may be purchased by calling the box office at 513-206-7049 or at the time of performance. Come and support our student actors and technicians who have worked diligently to produce this family-friendly play. We hope to see you there!
